 medieval French. The distinction was carried over into the King James Bible of 1611, and   Jacob   and <i>James</i> remain as separate names in English usage. Most European languages, however, make no such distinction, so that forms such as French   Jacques  , stand for both the Old and the New Testament names. This surname is also very common among African Americans. Compare   Jack  ."]},{"name":"Dmello","meanings":["Portuguese:  See  Demello  ."]}]},{"name":"Beatrice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["and French form of   Beatrix  , which was quite popular in England during the Middle Ages, and strongly revived in the 19th century. It is most famous as the name of Dante's beloved, and is borne by the elder (  b. 1988 ) of the Duke of York's daughters."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Beatrice DeMello was born in 1190, in Montluçon, Allier, Auvergne, France, her father, Renaud Ier de Mello, was 26 and her mother, Gertrude of Nesle, was 11. She had at least 1 son with Gasce De Chaumont En Vexin. She died in Somme, Picardie, France."},"et":{"1190–":"1190–Surnud","1190–Female":"1190–Surnud","1195–Female":"1195–Surnud","1180–1239":"1180–1239","1208–1250":"1208–1250","1165–1201":"1165–1201","1179–1229":"1179–1229","1190":"1190","1239":"1239","1179":"1179","1201":"1201","1165":"1165","1250":"1250","1195":"1195","1208":"1208","1229":"1229","1180":"1180","Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, Prantsusmaa","Montluçon, Allier, Auvergne, France":"Montluçon, Allier, Auvergne, Prantsusmaa","France":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1190–":"1190–Kuollut","1190–Female":"1190–Kuollut","1195–Female":"1195–Kuollut","1180–1239":"1180–1239","1208–1250":"1208–1250","1165–1201":"1165–1201","1179–1229":"1179–1229","1190":"1190","1239":"1239","1179":"1179","1201":"1201","1165":"1165","1250":"1250","1195":"1195","1208":"1208","1229":"1229","1180":"1180","Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, Ranska"